TRAVEL LOG THUS FAR

i'm warning you guys first hand...the keyboard here is a little different here and i get mixed up trying to get some of the right buttons....

so. i woke up at about 6 am on thursday, december 15. my mom helped me get the last things packed, i said goodbye to family and lucy, delivered some lastminute stuff to tasha, and we headed to mando's to pack my mom's subaru. After about three large suitcases in the pack, we figured out there was no way to fit all of our stuff. So, I called my dad and we used his truck to head over to the airport. I was a little nervous about how to navigate around SEATAC, but we did fine. We flew on a 737 from Seattle to Houston. The only part that turned out to be a big deal was the fact that I pysched myself out before the take off, visualizing it being horribley scary. and it wasn't pleasent....but much less scary than imagined. Fortunately, i got to sit next to a nice couple with a few-months old baby. the wife spoke spanish and so we chatted for a while...and the husband, a guero, recommonded certain techniques for wooing Mexican girls.

Houston airport was fine. However, the plane we took from Houston to Guadalajara was very small and I could feel every bit of turbulence. not my favorite, but thats why theres ipods. while we were flying, i tried really hard to figure out where the U.S. ended and Mexico began (it was dark). i couldn{t though. it all looked the same to me. also, made me realize how incredibly amazing planes and humanity are. relaly. honestly amazing.

Arrived in Guadalajara. I remember thinking, "Wow. I am in Mexico. Wow. wow. wow. wow." It was about 1130 when we arrived and whoever was supposed to pick us up didn{t show up for a while. then, finally, tio ruben showed up and picked us up in his shiny new ford. within 2 minutes from leaving the airport, we got pulled over. i thought, "how neat...i already get my first experience with the Mexican police." however, when the police walked up with a submachine gun, i tensed up just a little bit. The males were ordered out of the truck, and told to put our hands on the truck. THat was the first time i've ever been searched/frisked in my life. they checked my pockets, our wallets, ipods, everything. they told us it was just a preventative measure in searching for drugs. they actually didn't take any money. we then got lost for a bout an hour trying to find the way back to periban but i was too excited to rest my exhausted body. we found the way and drove for four hours, arriving us at abuelita's at around 5:30 am. by this time, i was TRULY exhausted as i'd been up for nealry 24 hours. mando's mom was very happy to see us and we crashed until about 10 in the morning. various people kept coming to wake us up but we were so tired that we kept sleeping. then, abuelita herself came into to talk to me. i don't remember everything she said, but i was truly humbled by her strong and loving presence. she asked me if i was catholic and we talked about religion for a while. though i had a hard tiem understanding a lot.

we got up and ate. The houses here are so different. the top floor of the house is where you hang the clothes and i love going up there just to look out over a lot of periban. we wondered around town, and i met lupita, and i saw the differences in culture of the cars, churches, houses, everything. I'm not going to write about cultural notions now, but for one thing, everyone here works. hard, and long. at the airport, at midnight, people were working. the food was great. (thus far, i've had so many different kinds of food, most of which i love. one thing that is very popular is chopped up fruit with chili powder and lime juice. i don{t know how many different times i've eaten this from a street vendor. i've had tortas, quesadillas, carne de puerco, arroz, jugo de fresa, tacos, carne asada, y mas que no puedo recorder ahorita.) One of the adopted family members of abuelita, chole, was seriously interested in me and we spent about half an hour around the table joking and laughing because she kept saying things in Spanish that I had a hard time understanding, like, "Tell your mom i will come help her clean in the united states so that i can be with you." after lounging around the house for a while, mando's mom told us that we were going on a tour to mexico city and we'd we leave that night.

TOUR

First, we drove to Uruapan at about 8 pm and all gathered, family by family, in Tia Imelda's house for a while. I met got to meet Mela's mother, father, and three sisters. We waited and waited for the tour bus to come. Much of the family, like 20 people, went with us. Mando had me worried because the of the drivers and the quality of the bus. I was most worried that I'd be so worried about the driver that i wouldn't be able to sleep (and after such a long journey the day before, this really had me worried). the bus was fine, the driver too, and i got a rough sleep. we drove all night through Mexico city and to the state of puebla. we went to a church and i offered a candle to nino doctor. then, for the first time, we wondered the street vendors and i bought a hammock. it's very hard to learn how to say no to the many many vendors that come up to you.

we then drove to another place that i forgot, and ate, and walked around. on this tour, there was a LOT of waiting. and you have to go the bathroom before you go driving because the bus doesnt have a bathroom. figuring this out, i said i needed to find a bathroom (which many people offer from there homes) and so pepe took me to find one. Here, using the bathroom costs you about three pesos and you get about 36 inches of toilet paper to go with it. i'd thought that the dirty chevron bathrooms i'd seen on family road trips were bad. nope.

then, we drove to a motel that wouldn't take us all in and so we stayed at the astor hotel, which was very nice with mahagony wood doors and hallway decor. then, the next day, yesterday, we went to the basilica. this was the whole point of going to mexico city, was to go to this church. imagine a huge church, and then multiply it by 5. The church plaza had so many people in it, that you were just encompassed by people on all sides pushing trying to get somewhere. the church was beautiful and huge and i'm slowly learning how to do things like persinar. after that, we drove to chalma and saw another huge and beautiful church. then, we waited, had dinner from the street vendors, and got on the bus. we stopped somewhere else ( i have no idea where or why) and we joked around oustide having fun spinning the bottle and seeing who had to dance with who, and drinking flavored vino, (really good) and eating some more and listening to music and then we discovered a free concert a little ways off and so all the jovenes went over and danced and listend to this great concert of bass, and lights, and durangeza. we got on the bus, and slept all the way to Mela's house.

=================================================

I'm sorry to bombard you with so many things all at once. THis is the first time i've had internet access and i'm not even remembering everything i wanted to say.  My stay is pretty amazing so far. there's challenges for me, like being really frustrated at not understanding everything, personal thoughts about religion, traveling nonstop until today, etc. but i'm still just as grateful for this experience and i'm doing my best to approach it a good way. i miss you all and i'll see you in 20 days...i think.

drop me an emial if you want....it might be a while, but i should get back to you....

Pretty much, I'm going to treat this as a travel log from now on. (Throughout my stay in Mexico). I'm going to attempt to show my parents how to access it and try to post every travel-related post public.

So far:

- I'm pumped to go as I believe that out of all the opportunities thus far in my life, this is either the biggest (or close to it) and I feel for once, like I deserve it as the Mexican culture and people have become a passion in my life.

- I'm pysched to have a forcred break.... absolutely no agenda from me. I will be immersed and therefore lacking time to think about the essay I submitted, the to do lists, dates, work, school, social stuff, etc.

- I've turned in two of my applications: Brown & Washington University in St. Louis. The whole college thing....damn.

- I started working on my senior project.....

Yeyah. 

Wassup AMy?

How did the discussion go down, all in all???
Thanks for those two nights in one thanksgiving break.

If I did how I think I did, then I got a D+.  That's if I did good, hah! I have one more small online test to take, but it's easy and it's worth nothing compared to the final.

Thanks, Josh. I like this idea.

1. Grab the nearest book.
2. Open the book to page 123.
3. Find the fifth sentence.
4. Post the text of the sentence in your journal along with these instructions.
5. Don't search around and look for the "coolest" book you can find. Do what's actually next to you.

Even of evil apartheid, Nelson said, "The truth does not suppress the dissenting voice."
[No fucking idea what the context is...but the book was published by a bunch of famous authors prior to the 2004 election to try and dissuade the American public from re-electing the BUll SHitter that is bush.]

From: The Future Dictionary of America.

Haven't updated in a long time. I know. I don't have the time now either. But shit. Here it's needed i guess.

THE PLAY

THE GORGE
Excited to work. Will be a blast. Gotta figure out scheduling shit for this summer.

EAGLE PROJECT
Received the best news of my whole project today. A certain donor is contributing a couple hundred dollars coupled with a another hundred from another organization. I'm very nervous about getting it done, but this helps.

RANDOM THOUGHTS
Yesterday I wanted to take off to Seattle and go to a Rave or a techno club. Then I get in my car, and I want to be a genuine cholo when I listen to Better Days.  Anyone ever tries to diss Tupac in any way, either fuck em' [sorry] or let me talk to them.  I admire and respect rappers and musicians and current figures who go out with a purpose, a story, and pour their spirit and soul into their work. I will probably return to Coldstone soon. Very mixed feelings. Oh well. Balls to the wall, right?

Honestly can't remember the rest of the shit now.  Is anyone else as forgetful as I am? Nope. Probably not. The American Spirit was with me earlier. It's interesting.

Hi: Hearing news of large donation from wonderful service organization
Lo: Not exercising and condemning myself for it. It's been this way because of my stupid Sprained MCL. No longer shall I let it ruin my cardiovascular life. Tomorrow I will ride my bike vigirously and relish in the exhaustion.

Peace

Here's some rattling thoughts....(seniors beware)

1) I can't believe for the life of me, that my friends (the class of 2005) who are basically my age (some younger)are leaving the K-12 schooling system.  They're venturing out into the world.  Shit.  That's daunting enough.  They'll be gone, and that means I'll be a senior.  I can barely comprehend this.
2) I'm going into my senior year pretty soon here.  What am I going to do?  What's my life going to consist of after High School? I don't even like it that much, but I can't imagine going out on your own and being an adult, and figuring out what you're going to do.  wow.
3) I've actually posted twice in one day. That's scary and I don't know I want to be that into it. Hmmm...will have to podner that one.  No, because pondering often leads to deep confusing thoughts.  Never mind. Man. This LJ thing...I don't know.  Do something.

tito regreso.  esta bien.

It's funny: Every time I post, I see the 'what music are you listening to?" button.  Then I go, "Oh shit.  I'd better turn something on."  Then, I quickly open itunes, and hit the 'next' button till a song comes up that I'm in the mood for.  Normally, I work with music on...but posting often only happens if I have time in the day. So I don't put music on for two minutes. ANYWAY----

It's hard: Don't take running, paddling, jogging, summersaulting, swimming, sprinting, climbing, hiking abilities for granted.  Right now, I can't do any of these things for fear of further injuring my sprained MCL (Medial Collateral Ligament).  The nasty part is, I'm one of those people who has to have excersise in order to function, to be okay, to be stable.  So I haven't gotten it recently and I think that's why I've had trouble being the least bit content in the past few days.  Ever feel like you don't want to be anywhere on the face of the planet? 

YESTERDAY'S HI'S & LOW'S

Hi: Cleaning my car thoroughly.  Amazing how easily it makes me feel more peaceful.  That sounds retarded, but shit, a clean car can do a lot for a person's attitude!  Actually sprayed the vinal in my car, vacuumed, took out EVERYTHING that didn't need to be in there. 

Low:  Not being able to go hiking with some friends...not being able to play soccer, not being able to get the endorphins up!
